(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[85],{307:function(e){e.exports={data:{posts:{totalCount:75,pageInfo:{totalPages:8,currentPage:6,isFirst:!1,isLast:!1},edges:[{node:{title:"Backwards compatibility on all PS3s?",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/21/backwards-compatibility-on-all-p-s3s",excerpt:"<p>Recently, reverse engineers and hackers have been able to extract the file used for PSN distributed Playstation 2 classics titles. Contrary to popular belief, these games are not reprogrammed ports of the games to the Playstation 3, but are complete emulations of the unmodified original game. Smart people have been able to implement this to allow the Sony designed emulator to run an extensive library of Playstation 2 games.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-21T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Backwards compatibility and IGN",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/08/backwards-compatibility-and-ign",excerpt:"\n",date:"2013-03-08T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"PS4 Backwards Compatibility: Offered by a peripheral?",image:"/media/images/blog/backcompat.png",path:"/blog/2013/03/03/p-s4-backwards-compatibility-offered-by-a-peripheral",excerpt:"<p>Backwards compatibility is a feature consumers might assume is available. Other than the Playstation 3, every video game console and handheld released since 2002 has offered it. Every smartphone or computer has it. Even when Apple switched processor architecture from PowerPC to Intel's x86 in 2006,Â  they designed the Rosetta software to allow older programs to work in the new systems.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-03T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:2}},{node:{title:"Being on IGN",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/01/being-on-ign",excerpt:"<p>With all the talk and recent happenings with IGN being purchased by Ziff Davis, things that I have often pondered have been brought to the forefront.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-01T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:3}},{node:{title:"8 reasons for backwards compatibility",image:"/media/images/blog/gta.jpg",path:"/blog/2013/02/27/8-reasons-for-backwards-compatibility",excerpt:'<p>At the recent Playstation event it was announced that Sony is moving to a new architecture with the Playstation 4, making it lack all backwards compatibility with current generation titles. On the fabulous and popular <a href="http://feeds.ign.com/ignfeeds/podcasts/beyond/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Podcast Beyond</a>, the dream team aren\'t concerned about this, saying that backwards compatibility isn\'t a feature they want or that many people will use.</p>\n',date:"2013-02-27T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:3}},{node:{title:"Uncle Ziff",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/02/23/uncle-ziff",excerpt:"<p>Things I liked and regularly used that Ziff Davis sold off, drastically downsized or outright killed:</p>\n",date:"2013-02-23T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"The End of 1UP. Long Live 1UP",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/02/22/the-end-of-1-up-long-live-1-up",excerpt:"\n",date:"2013-02-22T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Game Failings: An Update",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/02/17/game-failings-an-update",excerpt:"<p>A short video discussion talking about the current events around this blog. Also look out for a sneak peak of what titles will be Game Failing'd soon!</p>\n",date:"2013-02-17T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Go Go Power Rangers",image:"/media/images/blog/Rangers5.jpg",path:"/blog/2013/02/15/go-go-power-rangers",excerpt:"<p>This year marks the 20th anniversary since the Mighty Morphin' Power Rangers first aired on television. Very few other children's shows have achieved this longevity, especially in the unique case of having a complete cast turn around and a new story almost annually. And now the 20th season of the show is starting up with Power Rangers Megaforce. But before we look at that, some history about how this franchise got here.</p>\n",date:"2013-02-15T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:4}},{node:{title:"Game Failings: Fuel (2009)",image:"/media/images/blog/IMG_20130214_133143.jpg",path:"/blog/2013/02/13/game-failings-fuel-2009",excerpt:"<p>A Guinness World Record can be an awe inspiring thing. Going to school I remember browsing through the giant and heavy Book of Records, marveling at things like the man with the longest finger nails or the fastest car with three wheels. In 2008 the Gamer's Edition of Guinness World Records was first published, dedicated to records relating to video games and their associated culture. It received criticism for offering many subjective records, including stating what the best game is in a certain genre and ranking the games featuring the best graphics or villains. But not all the records followed this trend. Within the books pages were some true records of factual achievements, often demonstrating extremes of scale and size in video games.</p>\n",date:"2013-02-13T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:5}}]}}}}}]);